article.description: Seimone Augustus scored 20 points and No. 2 LSU shook off a slow start to beat Mississippi 71-54 Sunday.
article.headline: LSU matches program's best start
article.linkText: LSU rebounds from slow starts vs. Ole Miss to stay unbeaten
article.story:
BATON ROUGE, La. (AP) -- Seimone Augustus suspected that all she
had to do was start hitting her shots.

	   The freshman scored 20 points Sunday as LSU (No. 3 ESPN/USA Today, No. 2 AP) shook off a
slow start to beat Mississippi 71-54. The unbeaten Tigers won their
14th straight game to match the school's best start, set in the
1996-97 season.

	   "I knew my teammates would follow my lead,'' said Augustus, who
ranks 11th nationally in field-goal percentage. "We had people
sick, a lot of people were hurting, and we really weren't pumped
up, but we got over it.''

	   Coach Sue Gunter has 665 victories overall and is one win from
400 at LSU. Gunter ranks third on the NCAA career list behind
Tennessee's Pat Summitt and Texas' Jody Conradt.

	   Augustus was 7-for-11 from the field and 6-for-6 from the line.
She also had five assists. Ke-Ke Tardy came off the bench and
scored 10 points for LSU (14-0, 2-0 SEC).

	   "When you come off the bench you need to bring enthusiasm with
you,'' Tardy said. "That's what I wanted to bring the team.''

	   Carletta Brown led Mississippi with 18 points and Ambers Watts
added 14. The Lady Rebels (11-3, 1-1) are 0-5 in SEC road openers
under coach Ron Aldy.

	   "We just need to knock shots down,'' Brown said. "We were wide
open half the time and we couldn't knock them down.''

	   LSU started the game with four misses before DeTrina White
scored on a layup. The Tigers shot inconsistently in the first half
and were outrebounded by Ole Miss. The Rebels also struggled, going
10-of-25 from the field. They also turned the ball over 14 times.

	   The Tigers took the lead for good on a layup by Kisha James with
10:41 remaining and were up 33-27 at halftime.

	   LSU finally started hitting its shots in the second half.
Mississippi did not, going 5-of-19 in the first nine minutes of the
period.

	   "They found a way to pull their percentages up,'' Aldy said.
"We just continue to be in that funk we have been in. We've shot
the ball occasionally like this and it's very frustrating,
especially with the open looks we had.''

	   A free throw by White with 9:08 left stretched the Tigers' lead
to 53-43, and they were never in trouble after that.

	   Mississippi shot 33 percent from the field and hit 5-of-19
3-point baskets. LSU was 51 percent from the field and just 1-of-4
from 3-point range.

	   "We didn't expect to come down here and shoot 33 percent,''
Aldy said. "We knew we had to shoot the ball well and handle it
much wiser than we did.''
